And it will not be out ofplace to recall here what the famous philosopher Androcydes wrote to Alexander the Great in an attempt to restrain his intemperance: ‘ When you are about to drink wine, O King, remember that you are drinking the earth’s blood. Hemlock is poison to a human being and wine is poison to hemlock.' If Alexander had obeyed this advice, doubtless he would not have killed his friends⁶ in his drunken fits; so that in fact we are justified in saying that there is nothing else that is more useful for strength- ening the body, and also nothing more detrimental to our pleasures⁶ if moderatiori be lacking.
